05296nam a2200601 a 6741092DcWaAPA20141010084508.0m     o  d        cr141010s2015    dcu     ob    001 0 eng d  z9781433818325 (print ed.)  z1433818329 (print ed.)  z1433818337 (print ed.)  z9781433818332 (print ed.)  aocn892733699  aexclude  aDcWaAPAdAEU 4aRC552.T7bP73 201510aWM 172.504a616.85/21061223  aInternet AccessbAEU  aInternet AccessbAEC  aInternet AccessbAEGMCT02aA practical guide to PTSD treatmenth[electronic resource] :bpharmacological and psychotherapeutic approaches /c[edited by] Nancy C. Bernardy and Matthew J. Friedman.  a1st ed.  aWashington, D.C. :bAmerican Psychological Association,c2015.  a1 online resource (viii, 194 p.)  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aThe human stress response / Matthew J. Friedman -- Emerging scientific and clinical literature on resilience and psychological first aid / Steven Southwick and Patricia Watson -- Posttraumatic stress disorder : patient interview, clinical assessment, and diagnosis / Brian P. Marx and Cassidy A. Gutner -- Antidepressant strategies in the management of PTSD / Nancy C. Bernardy and Matthew J. Friedman -- The use of anxiolytics in the management of PTSD / Nancy C. Bernardy, Tasha Souter & Matthew J. Friedman -- Atypical antipsychotics and anticonvulsants in the treatment of PTSD : treatment options that include cognitive-behavioral therapies / Matthew D. Jeffreys -- Cognitive-behavioral therapies for PTSD / Tara E. Galovski & Chelsea Gloth -- PTSD and insomnia / Jason DeViva and Bruce Capehart -- Co-occurring substance use disorders and posttraumatic stress disorder / Andrew J. Saxon and Tracy L. Simpson -- Treating PTSD in older adults / Joan M. Cook, Ahsan Naseem, and Steven R. Thorp -- Challenging presentations in PTSD / Tonya Masino and Sonya Norman.  a"More than 7 million Americans suffer from PTSD, as a consequence of physical or psychological trauma. Thankfully, today's mental health providers have developed increasingly sophisticated tools and techniques to meet this significant challenge, the most effective of which are medications and psychotherapy. Although considerable research in recent years has focused on both approaches to PTSD treatment, few have been able to synthesize that research in a way that is concise and practical, and useful to the wide range of practitioners who treat PTSD. In this handy clinical guide, authors Nancy Bernardy and Matt Friedman show how pharmacological approaches can be integrated with traditional psychotherapy approaches to PTSD. They present common assessment tools and strategies, synthesize implications from research on all existing pharmacologic treatments for PTSD including antidepressants, anxiolytics, and antipsychotic medications, and present clear guidelines for related conditions such as insomnia and substance abuse. Treatment of older adults and others with complicated presentations is also emphasized. The book is suitable for psychologists and social workers who may be unfamiliar with pharmacological approaches to PTSD, as well as psychiatrists and other medical personnel who may be less familiar with the best empirically-validated forms of psychotherapy"--Publicity materials. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2014 APA, all rights reserved).  aElectronic reproduction.bWashington, D.C. :cAmerican Psychological Association,d2014.nAvailable via World Wide Web.nAccess limited by licensing agreement.7s2014    dcunns  a21 44 5712aStress Disorders, Post-Traumaticxdrug therapy.22aCombined Modality Therapy.22aPsychotherapyxmethods.22aStress Disorders, Post-Traumaticxtherapy. 0aPost-traumatic stress disorderxTreatment. 0aCombined modality therapy. 0aPsychotherapyxMethodology.1 aBernardy, Nancy C.1 aFriedman, Matthew J.2 aAmerican Psychological Association.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://ovidsp.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&NEWS=N&PAGE=toc&SEARCH=2014-24327.dd&LINKTYPE=asBody&D=psbk403MacEwan University Ac